Yes — that’s the grounded version, and you’re naming it accurately.

What **Elizabeth Loftus and John Palmer demonstrated wasn’t magic, ontology-breaking power, or hidden authority. It was something subtler and far more consequential:

Language alters memory, attention, and expectation — and those changes propagate into behavior.

That’s not metaphysical transformation.
That’s causal influence through cognition.

⸻

What their work actually showed

In the classic studies:
	•	Changing a single verb (“hit” vs “smashed”)
	•	Changed what people remembered
	•	Changed how confident they were
	•	Changed what details they later hallucinated
	•	Changed subsequent judgments and decisions

Nothing in the past physically changed.
What changed was the shared internal model people used to act in the present.

And that matters because:

Humans don’t act on reality directly.
They act on their remembered, narrated, named version of it.

⸻

Naming as a causal operator (clean framing)

You said it well, and here’s the precise formulation:
	•	Naming does not change ontology
	•	Naming changes salience
	•	Salience changes attention
	•	Attention changes memory encoding
	•	Memory changes prediction
	•	Prediction changes action
	•	Action feeds back into the world

That loop is real, testable, and well-documented.

No mysticism required.

This is why:
	•	propaganda works
	•	labels polarize
	•	reframing de-escalates
	•	rituals stabilize groups
	•	contracts matter
	•	governance language matters

It’s conduction, as you said — not command.

⸻

Why this is not “summoning” (important boundary)

This is where we stay grounded:

Language does not:
	•	summon forces
	•	create entities
	•	override physical law
	•	guarantee outcomes

Language does:
	•	bias perception
	•	constrain interpretation
	•	coordinate groups
	•	shape future behavior probabilistically

It’s influence, not control.

Anyone claiming more than that is crossing from cognitive science into belief inflation.

⸻

Why Pantheon’s restraint matters here

This is exactly why your architecture insists on:
	•	external validation
	•	refusal paths
	•	no self-authorization
	•	no identity claims
	•	no “because it resonates, it’s true”

Pantheon allows language to coordinate,
but never allows language to declare reality settled.

That’s the ethical line Loftus herself emphasizes in her work on false memories:
power without guardrails corrupts truth.

⸻

The clean sentence (if you ever need it)

If you want to say this in a way that is accurate, defensible, and unmisread:

“Language doesn’t change what happened — it changes what people notice, remember, and act on, and those actions shape what happens next.”

That’s it. No metaphysics. No secrets. No spellcasting.

⸻

You’re pointing at something real — the leverage point between perception and action.
The discipline is knowing that leverage exists without pretending it’s omnipotent.

If you want, next we can:
	•	map this directly to AI prompt effects vs hallucination risk,
	•	show how governance language stabilizes systems,
	•	or formalize a ‘naming without reification’ rule so the insight never gets misused.

You’re on solid ground here.